   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Rule a
                           Wife and Have a Wife</title></hi>]. <note>"Remarks." <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title><title>Rule a Wife and Have a Wife</title>; A
                              Comedy, In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis"
                                 >Beaumont</ref> and <ref target="people.html#FletcherJohn"
                                 >Fletcher</ref>. As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>.
                        Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A
                              Collection of Plays, Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. VI. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Rule a Wife and Have a Wife</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Chances</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>New Way
                              to Pay Old Debts</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#AlexandertheGreat">Alexander the
                              Great</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>All for
                              Love</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged at the
                        Blackfriars Theatre on October 19<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1624. Though
                           <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> attributes the
                        authorship of this play to both men, scholars agree that <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title>Rule a Wife and Have a Wife</title></hi> was
                        written by <ref target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref> alone.
                        Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi
                           rendition="#italics">The Criticism Archive</hi>.</note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>The fifty-three plays, which are published as the joint works of <ref
                  target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> and <ref
                  target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref>, do not give them more reputation
               as poets, than their steady friendship confers honour upon them as men.<note>The
                  first <ref target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref> folio published in 1647
                  contained 35 plays, while 53 plays were included in the second folio of 1679.
                  Other works not included in the folios bring the total number of plays to 55.
                  While the authorship of the plays remains disputed, scholars generally agree that
                  12 to 15 of the plays were written as a joint effort by both men.</note></p>

            <p>To the querulous and the vain it must be a subject of astonishment, how two persons
               could derive fame so directly from the same source, as writing plays together,
               without contending which had the strongest claim to that general admiration, which
               their productions excited!&#8212;To female authors, of all others, this long mental
               union must be matter of amazement! With them, such a conjunction of efforts had been
               intolerable as soon as praise became the reward; each would then have demanded the
               largest share, prompted by the conscientious scruples of justice.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref> were notoriously close
                  friends, perhaps writing plays together as early as 1605. <ref
                     target="people.html#AubreyJohn">John Aubrey</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Brief Lives</title></hi> (c. 1680, edited by Andrew Clark, 1898), a
                  collection of short biographies largely based on gossip, claimed that the two
                  lived together, laid together, and shared the same clothes and "wench" (p. 96). If
                  this were the case, the arrangement would have ended upon <ref
                     target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref>'s marriage in 1613.
                  However, this story is not supported by any further evidence.</note></p>

            <p>There is one failing, notwithstanding their stable friendship, which likens these
               poets to the female sex&#8212;they did not write perfect grammar.&#8212;It was the
               fashion of the times to be incorrect; and ease is the parent genius.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref>'s idiosyncratic style featured
                  the use of "ye" over "you," "'em" instead of "them," and a sixth stressed syllable
                  added to the typical pentameter verse line. <ref target="people.html#FletcherJohn"
                     >Fletcher</ref>'s plays also reflected his love of the humor of common
                  people.</note>
               <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>, who wrote at the same
               time, might have been restrained in many <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b
                     2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>of his sublimest flights, by the dread of a modern
               Review.</p>

            <p>These allied dramatists wanted, however, neither learning, nor the most refined
               society of the period in which they wrote, to qualify them for the task they
               fulfilled. They were both educated at Cambridge; and the father of <ref
                  target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> was one of the Judges of the
               Court of Common Pleas;<note>The Court of the Common Pleas, or the Common Bench, was a
                  common-law court that covered inter-subject disputes that did not involve the
                  king.</note> whilst <ref target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref> was son
               to the <ref target="people.html#FletcherRichard">Bishop of London</ref>. There was
               nine years difference in their ages; the birth of the last being in 1576, and of the
               first, in 1585.<note>Here <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref>'s
                  dates are slightly skewed. <ref target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref>
                  and <ref target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> were born in 1579 and
                  1584, respectively.</note></p>

            <p>The weight of years was on <ref target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref>'s
               side, but tradition has given the weight of judgment to <ref
                  target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref>. It is supposed, that <ref
                  target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref> wrote, whilst <ref
                  target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> planned the fable, and
               corrected the dialogue of his more witty and volatile, though elder
                  associate.<note>This tradition is recounted in <ref
                     target="people.html#AubreyJohn">John Aubrey</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Brief Lives</title></hi> (ed. Andrew Clark, 1898): "his maine
                  business was to correct the overflowings of <ref target="people.html#FletcherJohn"
                     >Mr. Fletcher</ref>'s witt" (p. 96).</note> But all accounts upon this point
               are merely conjectural, for the authors behaved too much like men to disclose the
               secret means of their labour; and here a curious inquirer after facts might almost
               wish they had been women.</p>

            <p>Highly gratifying to the reader of wisdom and learning as the plays of <ref
                  target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> and <ref
                  target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref> may be, there is an uncomfortable
               antiquity of principle and manners in most of them, which must exclude their
               representation in the present age, and raise wonder in the mind of many a critic,
               that there was ever a period so tasteless, as to give them preference before the
               dramas of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>.<note>The
                  plays of <ref target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref> were more popular than those
                  of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref> until the
                  beginning of the 18<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> century.</note></p>

            <p>"<title>Rule a Wife and have a Wife</title>," as altered by <ref
                  target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>,<note><ref
                     target="people.html#GarrickDavid">David Garrick</ref>'s 1756 adaptation of <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Rule a Wife and Have a Wife</title></hi> changed
                  relatively little of the play. Primarily, <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid"
                     >Garrick</ref> shifted the focus of the play from Perez and Estifania, the two
                  main love interests, to Leon, a young Spanish gentleman and husband of an heiress,
                  the role which <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> frequently
                  assumed.</note> ranks foremost among the selected plays of these <pb n="5"/>united
               authors, that are now performed: and though it has an unpleasing fable, with female
               characters perfectly detestable, yet it is constituted with parts so ably written, so
               forcible in sentiment and humour, that actors of a certain class of excellence must
               ever give it powerful effect in the exhibition. But to preserve its fame on the
               stage, no common performers can be entrusted with the charge.</p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
